U.S. officials have forced Musk to step down as chairman of Tesla's board
U.S. businessman Elon Musk will step down as chairman of Tesla’s board of directors at the request of U.S. authorities.
To settle the claims of the Federal Securities and Exchange Commission, the entrepreneur will also pay $20 million.
According to CNBC, the pre-trial agreement with the agency allows Musk to remain in the leadership position at Tesla.
At the same time, he is obliged to pay $20 million and leave the position of Chairman of the Board of Directors within 45 days from the date of the agreement and for at least three years.
Two independent directors will be appointed in his place.
It is clarified that the agreement still has to be approved by the court.
On September 28, it became known that the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission accused Musk of misleading shareholders with a statement about the availability of sufficient funds to buy back shares of this company and filed a lawsuit against the entrepreneur.
It is about the publication of a businessman on Twitter, where he said he wanted to buy Tesla shares for $420 a piece, but he never did.
After the tweet, the company’s shares grew by almost 11%.
