Elon Musk is forced to step down as chairman of Tesla’s board of directors.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk have settled their fraud case.
This is reported by CNBC News.
According to the TV channel, within the framework of the agreements reached, Masku will have to leave the post of chairman of the board of directors of Tesla.
At the same time, the commission allowed Musk to retain the position of head of Tesla.
The founder of Tesla will also have to pay an administrative fine of $20 million.
The same amount will be required from Tesla.
The money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company must appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American entrepreneur who is on the list of the 50 richest people of the planet according to Forbes magazine.
He is the head of space corporation SpaceX, neurotech company Neuralink and electric car developer Tesla, as well as the co-founder of Paypal.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has previously sued Tesla CEO Elon Musk over his tweet about a possible buyout of the company.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy all shares on the stock exchange at a fixed price of $420.
The $420 share price was set “due to the importance of this number in marijuana culture,” Bloomberg said, citing Stephen Pekin, co-director of the commission’s security department.
At the same time, Elon Musk subsequently renounced his plans to buy back the shares.
Commenting on a lawsuit filed against him by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said he considered the allegations of fraud unfounded, adding that he was very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
“Honesty is the most important value in my life, and the facts will prove that I have not violated it in any way,” the businessman told CNBC.
In August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a class action lawsuit against Musk, complaining about the financial losses.
The plaintiffs claimed that the businessman's posts brought them losses.
In particular, one shareholder said the businessman’s tweets were misleading, prompting Tesla stock sellers to buy papers at artificially overpriced prices to cover their positions.
Other plaintiffs also noted that Elon Musk’s careless statements led to sharp course fluctuations.
In September, Elon Musk also accused the head of the research company Citron Research of exchange machinations.
Meanwhile, if Musk could not settle his dispute with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, he would be threatened with dismissal from the company’s management and even jail.
This was stated, in particular, by the former chairman of the commission Harvey Pitt.
Musk is “a good guy who doesn’t know how to run a car company.”
