The Ministry noted that all violations were being checked.
“The Ministry will act in accordance with the law so that citizens can safely use the constitutional right to freely express their will.
We call on citizens to comply with the laws and refrain from any violations of public order and tranquility and any violation of the secrecy of voting," the representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs said.
During the referendum on Sunday, citizens were asked to answer one question: “Do you support EU and NATO membership by accepting an agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Hellenic Republic?”
The referendum is intended to resolve a 27-year dispute between Macedonia and Greece over the name of the former Yugoslav republic, which coincides with the name of the northern Greek region.
The Foreign Ministers of Macedonia and Greece signed an agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav Republic on June 17 during a solemn ceremony on the shores of Lake Prespa, which runs the border between the two countries.
It provides for the use of the name "Republic of North Macedonia".
This treaty should resolve not only a long-standing dispute over the name of the country, but also open the way for Skopje to NATO and the EU.
