Kosachev: At the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly, the topic of Russia was almost absent in a negative way
The head of the Federation Council Committee on International Affairs, Konstantin Kosachev, believes that the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly is successful for Russia and does not exclude that it will be able to become a turning point in the perception of Russia as an integral participant in the solution of global global problems.
“The uniqueness of the current 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric that we have already almost become accustomed to in recent years with regard to Russia has now been somewhat more muted,” the senator said in an interview published Sunday by the Russian newspaper.
He explained that in previous years the Russian Federation was sometimes “described as one of the three main threats to humanity, then along with Ebola fever, then along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this rank, at least, a fairly common, in the presentation of a group of Western countries, which is on this account.
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, “the theme of Russia was practically absent in a negative way”.
"If you carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Germany, I do not take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, at least, the choir was not completely accurate," - drew the attention of the politician, noting that Russia "was no longer a wall, about which the puddles are trained.
The head of the specialized committee of the Council does not rule out that this indicates a trend that, in his opinion, "will highlight the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although this trend may fully manifest itself in a year, in two, three."
“I do not rule out that the current session may be reversible in some sense,” Kosachev admitted, explaining that “too many examples of how with the connection of Russia it is possible to move forward in international affairs.”
As an example, he cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea.
"Unfortunately, this is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time," he added.
This is because, he believes, there is an "adequate, healthy perception of Russia as not just possible - an integral participant in solving the global problems of today".
“I don’t want to make a mistake, but I have the feeling that we’re going through a point where movement is no longer a backward movement, it’s a forward movement,” he said.
Another "interesting and important feeling" in this context, Kosachev called "the request for the Russian vision of how the modern world should develop."
"I attended a lot of meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly] of the Minister of Foreign Affairs Sergei Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I was very pleased to see that if a year or two or five years ago, the Russian view of what is happening in the world is not the same.
According to him, this is due to the fact that "the so-called new liberal order, which is personified with the West, has no answers to the questions of how to solve the world problems due to the obvious lack of ideas in the global space, the lack of ideas about how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the lack of problems of the Middle East, the shortage of ideas about how to solve the problems of the Middle East and the Middle East".
"And here the demand for the Russian vision is becoming more and more obvious," Kosachev said, stressing that he believes that in this sense, "the current session is successful for the work of the Russian delegation, successful for Russia."
