ADG became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant “Alternative for Germany” is breaking another record in popularity, and Angela Merkel’s ratings are falling.
It seems that the Germans have become seriously tired of Angela Merkel’s immigration policy, which has made the country a desirable destination for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
This is most evident in recent social polls, according to which the anti-immigrant party "Alternative for Germany" is becoming increasingly popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, AdG broke another record, climbing to the second line in the ranking of popular sympathies.
The right-wing conservatives, with 17 percent of the popular vote, managed to circumvent the Social Democrats, with about 16 percent of them.
The one percentage point gap can be attributed to statistical error, but it is not to be noted the fact that the AdG created in 2013 from a small group of eurosceptic economists has managed to turn into a serious political force.
The overall leadership continues to hold the CSU/CSU governing bloc, which has about 30 per cent.
